d F.C. seasons]]\n[[Category:2002\u201303 FA Premier League by team|Manchester United]]\n[[Category:English football championship-winning seasons|2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n | club               = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n | season             = 2002\u201303\n | manager            = [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]]\n | chairman           = [[Martin Edwards]]\n | league             = [[2002\u201303 FA Premier League|Premier League]]\n | league result      = 1st\n | cup1               = [[2002\u201303 FA Cup|FA Cup]]\n | cup1 result        = Fifth Round\n | cup2               = [[2002\u201303 Football League Cup|League Cup]]\n | cup2 result        = Runners-up\n | cup3               = [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]]\n | cup3 result        = Quarter-finals\n | league topscorer   = <br />[[Ruud van Nistelrooy]] (25)\n | season topscorer   = <br />[[Ruud van Nistelrooy]] (44)\n | highest attendance = 67,721 vs [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]] (3 May 2003)\n | lowest attendance  = 47,848 vs [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] (5 November 2002)\n | average attendance = 67,602<!-- (1,284,440 attendance / 19 LEAGUE games) = 67,602.105263157 = 67,602 -->\n | pattern_la1        = _manutdh0204 |pattern_b1 = _manutdh0204 |pattern_ra1 = _manutdh0204 |pattern_sh1 = _manutdh0204 |pattern_so1 = _mufc0204h\n | leftarm1           = E20E0E |body1 = E20E0E |rightarm1 = E20E0E |shorts1 = FFFFFF |socks1 = 000000\n | pattern_la2        = _redborderthin |pattern_b2 = _manutda0203 |pattern_ra2 = _redborderthin |pattern_sh2 = _manutda0203 |pattern_so2 = _manutda0203\n | leftarm2           = FFFFFF |body2 = FFFFFF |rightarm2 = FFFFFF |shorts2 = 000000 |socks2 = FFFFFF\n | pattern_la3        = _thinblackborder |pattern_b3 = _manutd30203 |pattern_ra3 = _thinblackborder |pattern_sh3 = _manutd30203 |pattern_so3 = _manutd30203 \n | leftarm3           = 0000C0 |body3 = 0000C0 |rightarm3 = 0000C0 |shorts3 = 0000C0 |socks3 = 0000C0\n | prevseason         = [[2001\u201302 Manchester United F.C. season|2001\u201302]]\n | nextseason         = [[2003\u201304 Manchester United F.C. season|2003\u201304]]\n}}\nThe 2002\u201303 season was [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]'s 11th season in the [[Premier League]], and their 28th consecutive season in the top division of [[Football in England|English football]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/seasons/season2003.html |title=Manchester United Season 2002/03 |accessdate=8 October 2007 |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk }}</ref> This season saw the club finish at the top of the [[Premier League]] table, after their lowest finish in the history of the Premier League the previous season, when they came third. In order to win the title, the team had to pull [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] back from an eight-point lead at the beginning of March. United also finished as runners-up in the [[Football League Cup|League Cup]], with [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] eventually taking the prize. The club also broke the English transfer record for the third time in just over a year as they paid \u00a329.1&nbsp;million for [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] [[Defender (association football)|defender]] [[Rio Ferdinand]].\n\nAt the end of the season, United midfielder [[David Beckham]] decided to move to [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in a \u00a325&nbsp;million deal, having spent 12 years at United (eight of them as a first-team regular). Meanwhile, 37-year-old centre-back [[Laurent Blanc]] announced his retirement from playing. Fellow centre-back [[David May (footballer)|David May]] was finally given a free transfer after nine years at the club, the last five of which had seen his first team opportunities limited to a handful of appearances.\n\n==Season review==\nAfter ending the [[2001\u201302 FA Premier League|previous season]] by surrendering the title to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at home and finishing third behind rejuvenated [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]], [[Alex Ferguson]] reiterated his desire to dominate English football by signing a three-year contract in the late winter of 2002.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ferguson signs new deal |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/1843622.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 February 2002 |accessdate=11 May 2008 }}</ref> By the end of the season, Ferguson got his wish and bagged Manchester United their fifteenth domestic league title, thanks largely to the form of striker [[Ruud van Nistelrooy]] who scored an impressive 25 goals during the run-in.<ref>{{cite web |title=Van Nistelrooy nets Golden Boot |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/3018753.stm |date=11 May 2003}}</ref> The manager also assembled a new defence which included new signing [[Rio Ferdinand]], whose deal broke the transfer record in English football and indeed, the world record for a defender.\n\nThe Red Devils started their quest to regain the Premier League title at home to newly promoted [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and claimed all three points thanks to super-sub [[Ole Gunnar Solskj\u00e6r]]'s late goal. Results didn't flow as Ferguson hoped and as early autumn approached, Manchester United had made their worst start since the inauguration of the Premier League, lying in 10th place.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ferguson rues poor start |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/2288906.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 September 2002 |accessdate=11 May 2008 }}</ref> Things didn't get better as losses to [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] and [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] were eclipsed by a derby day defeat to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in November which allowed a four-point gap to open between themselves and leaders Liverpool. Following an empathic win against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], the team embarked on a run of wins that included rivals Liverpool, struggling West Ham and champions Arsenal to help their Premier League challenge gather ominous momentum. Although they slumped to defeat on Boxing Day at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], the team were in third place, five points short of table-toppers Arsenal at the turn of the year.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ferguson's best yet |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/m/man_utd/2984545.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2008 }}</ref>\n\nThe Middlesbrough loss on 22 December turned out to be their last league defeat of the season, as a series of late home wins against Sunderland and Chelsea in January helped pile the pressure somewhat on runaway leaders Arsenal, who were struggling with a minor goalkeeping crisis. After United drew at Bolton in the late evening kick-off on 22 February, Arsenal had the chance to open a five-point gap at the Premier League summit if they won at Maine Road. A five-star performance ensured this through a rampant display of attacking football that virtually put one hand on the trophy. However the difference in the title race was  later whittled down to two after Blackburn completed a sensational double over the reigning champions at home while United recorded a victory over Aston Villa thanks to a [[David Beckham]] goal.\n\nApril began with a ruthless win at Old Trafford against Liverpool, which helped them reclaim top spot albeit temporarily. However, [[Kolo Tour\u00e9]]'s late own goal gifted Aston Villa a point when Arsenal perhaps should have taken all three. By the end of the week, just goal difference separated the top two, favouring the Gunners.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ten weeks that turned the title |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2992107.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2008 }}</ref> A 6\u20132 rout at Newcastle preceded the game of the season: against Arsenal at Highbury. A 2\u20132 draw didn't prove to be decisive, but it was advantage Manchester United, who maintained a three-point lead, although the Gunners had a game in hand and a slightly superior goal difference.<ref>{{cite news |title=United on pole as Campbell sees red |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/apr/17/match.arsenal |publisher=Guardian News and Media |work=The Guardian |date=17 April 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2012 }}</ref> Despite more European disappointment \u2013 this time at the hands of [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] through an impressive performance by [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Ronaldo kills United's dreams |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2003/apr/24/championsleague.sport |publisher=Guardian News and Media |work=The Guardian |date=24 April 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2012 }}</ref> \u2013 a comeback by Bolton Wanderers dented Arsenal's hopes of retaining the double and installed Manchester United as sole favourites to win the league. They didn't bluff, cruising to a 4\u20131 home win against [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd close in on title |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2968005.stm|publisher=BBC Sport |date=3 May 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2012 }}</ref> and clinching their eighth title in eleven seasons after Arsenal lost at home to Leeds a day later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Viduka hands title to Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/2968015.stm|publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2003 |accessdate=11 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\nManchester United wrapped up their successful league campaign with a 2\u20131 victory at [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], David Beckham scored United's leveller in what was his last appearance for the club.\n\n==Pre-season and friendlies==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Opponents\n!H/A\n!Result<br />F\u2013A\n!Scorers\n!Attendance\n|- bgcolor=\"#ddffdd\"\n|20 July 2002\n|[[Shelbourne F.C.|Shelbourne]]\n|A\n|5\u20130\n|[[